subsection.p:
Applying Ohm's law to the two resistors separatelty gives us currents through the individual resitors immediately. 

	 I_1 \amp  = \dfrac{\Delta\phi_1}{R_1} = \dfrac{V}{R_1}
	 I_2 \amp  = \dfrac{\Delta\phi_2}{R_2} = \dfrac{V}{R_2} 

These show that if R_1 \gt R_2, then I_1 \lt I_2. That is, higher current will flow through the branch with smaller resistance. If a branch has no resistance, then there will be no current will be left to flow through any other branch. Such as branch is called a short in the circuit.

solution.p:
(c)
The equivalent resistance across the source is the equivalent resistance of parallel resitors.

	I \amp =  \dfrac{V}{R_\text{parallel}} =  \dfrac{20\text{ V}}{75\ \Omega} = 267\text{ mA}
